School and Library Subscribers JOIN LOGIN Activate Your Free Trial! stories quizzes galleries lists Neoplatonism Article Web sites Read View History Edit Feedback Neoplatonism, the last school of Greek philosophy, given its definitive shape in the 3rd century ce by the one great philosophical and religious genius of the school, Plotinus. The ancient philosophers who are generally classified as Neoplatonists called themselves simple “Platonists,” as did the philosophers of the Renaissance and the 17th century whose ideas derive from ancient Neoplatonism. See Platonism. Comments Share SHARE Email Print Cite You may also be interested in... Platonism philosophy list of philosophers Cambridge Platonists existentialism nihilism Marxism utilitarianism humanism pragmatism Stoicism empiricism Keep exploring Exploration and Discovery The Ottoman Empire and the Middle East To Kill a Mockingbird 7 Alphabet Soup Agencies that Stuck Around 5 Wacky Facts about the Births and Deaths of U.S. Presidents What made you want to look up Neoplatonism? To From Subject Comments (Please limit to 900 characters) Cancel BRITANNICA QUIZZES Canines vs. Felines Africa’s Physical Features Cervantes See More Quizzes MORE QUIZZES Who Wrote It? A Study of Religion: Fact or Fiction? Famous Serial Killers See More Quizzes About Us About Our Ads Partner Program Contact Us Privacy Policy Terms of Use ©2016 Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc. Citations MLA style: "Neoplatonism". Encyclopædia Britannica. Encyclopædia Britannica Online. Encyclopædia Britannica Inc., 2016. Web. 14 Apr. 2016 <http://www.britannica.com/topic/Neoplatonism>. APA style: Neoplatonism. (2016). In Encyclopædia Britannica. Retrieved from http://www.britannica.com/topic/Neoplatonism Harvard style: Neoplatonism. 2016. Encyclopædia Britannica Online. Retrieved 14 April, 2016, from http://www.britannica.com/topic/Neoplatonism Chicago Manual of Style: Encyclopædia Britannica Online, s. v. "Neoplatonism", accessed April 14, 2016, http://www.bri